body:
Rustc doesn't report the right error when an enum variant doesn't exist and the enum variant contains an anonymous struct. It works well if the enum variant contains a value, or if it's an empty enum variant.

```Rust

enum Test {
    One,
    #[cfg(test)]
    Two{
        foo: String,
    },
    #[cfg(test)]
    Three,
     #[cfg(test)]
     Four(String)
}  

fn main() {
    works();
    works_too();
    fails();
}


fn works(){
    let y = Test::Three; // here we have the expected error: `variant not found in `Test``
}

fn works_too(){
    let y = Test::Four("yolo".to_owned()); // here we have the expected error: `variant not found in `Test``
}

fn fails(){
    let y = Test::Two{foo: "yolo".to_owned()}; // here, the error is not what it should be (`ambiguous associated type`)
}
```

## Meta

`rustc --version --verbose`:

```
rustc 1.28.0-nightly (2a1c4eec4 2018-06-25)
binary: rustc
commit-hash: 2a1c4eec40527de45b9d9b81672c8b9220d554fc
